INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'e4cef8a3-d0a8-4c18-a51a-acb53bf9a4bf',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$SvelteKit Layout-Level Toast, Modal & Shared Loading UI — Global UI Patterns Done Right$escape$,
  $escape$SvelteKit's nested layout system makes it trivial to wire up global UI without prop-drilling or a state management library. Drop a `+layout.svelte` at the root and use a writable store to drive toasts and modals from anywhere in the app.

Define a `toastStore` and `modalStore` in `$lib/stores/ui.ts`. Your root layout subscribes to both and renders the overlay components once — they're always mounted, always reactive. Child routes trigger them by importing the store and calling `toastStore.show(...)` or `modalStore.open(...)`.

For shared loading UI, SvelteKit exposes the `$navigating` store from `$app/stores`. It's non-null during any client-side navigation. Bind a progress bar or skeleton overlay directly to `$navigating` in `+layout.svelte` — no lifecycle hooks needed. Pair it with `+loading.svelte` (introduced via route-level `+page.svelte` async `load`) for streamed data skeletons scoped to a layout segment. Use `+layout.ts` with `await parent()` to sequence data dependencies, keeping the root layout's loading state decoupled from nested route fetches.$escape$,
  $escape$<!-- src/routes/+layout.svelte -->
<script lang="ts">
  import { navigating } from '$app/stores';
  import { toastStore } from '$lib/stores/ui';
  import Toast from '$lib/components/Toast.svelte';
  import Modal from '$lib/components/Modal.svelte';
</script>

{#if $navigating}
  <div class="progress-bar" />
{/if}

<Toast messages={$toastStore.messages} />
<Modal config={$modalStore} />

<slot />$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
