INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'c1160d8c-7f23-443e-b949-dd3b91dfeb2c',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$SvelteKit Quality Gates — Type-Safe Route Params, CLI Sync, and Adapter-Aware Previews$escape$,
  $escape$SvelteKit's CLI ships a `sync` command that generates `.svelte-kit/types/` — the source of the `./$types` virtual module every route imports. Run `svelte-kit sync` before `svelte-check` in CI, or let both fire automatically via `npm run check` (scaffolded by `create-svelte` by default).

Route params get strict types through `./$types`: import `PageServerLoad` or `PageLoad` in your `+page.server.ts` / `+page.ts`, and `params` becomes typed against your file-system segments automatically. A route at `src/routes/posts/[slug]/+page.server.ts` surfaces `params.slug: string` — no manual casting. For optional or rest segments (`[[optional]]`, `[...rest]`), the generated `RouteParams` type reflects correct optionality.

For preview deployments, `vite preview` serves the Vite-built output locally but skips adapter-specific runtime behavior. For Cloudflare, use `wrangler pages dev .svelte-kit/cloudflare`; for Vercel, use `vercel dev`. These surface edge cases — missing platform bindings, broken `PLATFORM` env vars — that `vite preview` silently swallows.

Gate your CI pipeline with `svelte-kit sync && svelte-check --tsconfig ./tsconfig.json` to catch broken param types and `.svelte` type errors before any branch merges.$escape$,
  $escape$// src/routes/posts/[slug]/+page.server.ts
import type { PageServerLoad } from './$types';
import { error } from '@sveltejs/kit';

export const load: PageServerLoad = async ({ params, fetch }) => {
  // params.slug: string — typed by svelte-kit sync, not hand-written
  const res = await fetch(`/api/posts/${params.slug}`);
  if (!res.ok) error(404, 'Post not found');
  return { post: await res.json() as App.Post };
};$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
